quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to make the word-spacing 15px:
[!raw!]
p { 
   {0}-spacing: {1}px;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The word-spacing Property[/h1]

The word-spacing property specifies the [b]space between words[/b] in a text. Just like the letter-spacing property, you can set the word-spacing values as [b]normal[/b], [b]length[/b], and [b]inherit[/b]. 

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<p class="normal">This paragraph has no additional word-spacing applied.</p>
<p class="px">This paragraph is word-spaced at 30px.</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="533"]p.normal { 
   [b]word-spacing: normal[/b];
}
p.px { 
   [b]word-spacing: 30px[/b];
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2609" width="100%"]
[note]When a weird spacing is used, and it is necessary to keep the selected paragraph with normal word spacing, the [b]normal[/b] option is usually used.[/note]

[h1]Measurement Units[/h1]

To define an extra space between words, you can use positive measurement values like[b] px, pt, pc, cm, mm, inches, em, [/b]and[b] ex[/b].
Negative values are also permitted. Here is an example to show the difference. 

[b]The HTML:[/b][code format="html" ]<p class="positive">This paragraph is word-spaced at 20px.</p>
<p class="negative">This paragraph is word-spaced at -5px.</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="raw" codeId="534"]p.positive { 
  [b] word-spacing: 20px[/b];
}
p.negative { 
   [b]word-spacing: -5px[/b];
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2610" width="100%"]
